Another innovation could be the introduction of **cross-source temporal stratification**, where datasets are split not just by time, but by the emergence of novel misinformation narratives, forcing models to generalize to unseen topics from unseen sources at future times. This mimics real-world dynamics more faithfully.

We should also consider benchmarking against a new metric: **generalization gap under source-time disjoint splits**, which quantifies performance drop when moving from random splits to causally rigorous ones. A small gap would indicate robustness; a large one flags overfitting to artifacts.

By rethinking splits as an active component of model evaluation—not just a procedural step—we can shift the field toward more trustworthy and deployable systems. This work would align with our team’s strength in diagnostic evaluation and causal ML, while offering a foundational contribution that could redefine best practices in misinformation research.
